As an introverted, creative individual who is self-employed and very privacy-conscious, running a business shouldn't feel so awkward, but sometimes it does. Most online resources and mentors tell you to approach large (evil) tech companies in an extroverted way. You're supposed to advertise here, follow algorithms, share your charm and personality. Get verified on that platform, stay online all day, answer questions with your own videos, and respond immediately. Videos, videos, and more videos.
1/3
For me, this year is a year of transition.
I no longer want to dedicate my money, data, and energy to large tech companies, nor do I want to listen to the advice of mentors who only impose a one-size-fits-all, outward-looking solution on everyone. I am exploring new business models and striving to overcome a long-held belief that success can only be achieved by doing things in a specific way.
Good luck to me!
The first step has been taken.
I left Facebook, removed all Meta and Pinterest trackers from my website, and deleted my personal WhatsApp account.
Yesterday, I removed the last external tracker from my website - Google Analytics, and I felt great.
In order to better support GDPR, I recently subscribed to a European CRM service and will be migrating my business to it over the next few weeks.
I transferred my MX records to Proton, and now I have complete SPF, DKIM, and DMARC configurations without having to pay Google for basic email verification.
3/3
